  <section class="system-section system-section--architecture">
    <div class="container system-two-up">
      <div>
        <p class="system-kicker">The architecture</p>
        <h2>Clean separation.</h2>
        <p>
          Your data stays in your database. Work events are recorded separately. Agents do the
          execution. Orchestration moves work forward. Verification protects quality.
        </p>
        <p>Each part does one job. That&rsquo;s why it stays lightweight.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="system-stack">
        <article><span>Top layer</span><strong>Agents + Orchestration</strong></article>
        <article><span>Middle layer</span><strong>Coordination and event record</strong></article>
        <article><span>Bottom layer</span><strong>Application database</strong></article>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="system-section system-section--consensus">
    <div class="container system-two-up">
      <div>
        <p class="system-kicker">The coordination layer</p>
        <h2>A system for tracking work, not storing data.</h2>
        <p>
          Dreamborn records work as it happens: task created, task claimed, work completed,
          review triggered, verification passed, state updated.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is an append-only event record. It is not your database. It is not storing
          business data. Internally, we use consensus to keep this record consistent. But this
          is not blockchain theater. It is a lightweight coordination layer for work.
        </p>
      </div>
      <div class="system-event-stream">
        <span>task.created</span>
        <span>task.claimed</span>
        <span>work.completed</span>
        <span>review.triggered</span>
        <span>verification.passed</span>
        <span>state.updated</span>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

